JOHANNESBURG - Farmers have been urged to be vigilant in checking whether their poultry is showing signs of the H5N8 virus.There's been an outbreak on a farm near the Vaal River on the border between Gauteng and Mpumalanga.READ: SA bans poultry, egg imports from ZimbabweSouth African poultry exports have ceased due to the outbreak.At least 5,000 birds on the commercial broiler breeder farm have died.While a further 19,000 have had to be culled.The farm has since been quarantined.The virus is usually spread by wild migratory birds and is passed on to domestic poultry.The more common H5N1 strain of bird flu has infected humans, in rare cases mostly in AsiaeNCA